#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:1
msgid "Appendix: The Life Cycle of a Signal"
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:3
msgid ""
"Three questions commonly arise at the intermediate level when using Leptos:"
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:4
msgid ""
"How can I connect to the component lifecycle, running some code when a "
"component mounts or unmounts?"
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:5
msgid ""
"How do I know when signals are disposed, and why do I get an occasional "
"panic when trying to access a disposed signal?"
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:6
msgid ""
"How is it possible that signals are `Copy` and can be moved into closures "
"and other structures without being explicitly cloned?"
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:8
msgid ""
"The answers to these three questions are closely inter-related, and are each "
"somewhat complicated. This appendix will try to give you the context for "
"understanding the answers, so that you can reason correctly about your "
"application's code and how it runs."
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:10
msgid "The Component Tree vs. The Decision Tree"
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:12
msgid "Consider the following simple Leptos app:"
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:23
msgid "\"+1\""
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:25
msgid "\"Even numbers are fine.\""
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:35 src/appendix_life_cycle.md:107
msgid "\"count is odd and is {}\""
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:47
msgid "\"You're an odd duck.\""
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:52
msgid ""
"All it does is show a counter button, and then one message if it's even, and "
"a different message if it's odd. If it's odd, it also logs the values in the "
"console."
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:54
msgid ""
"One way to map out this simple application would be to draw a tree of nested "
"components:"
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:61
msgid "Another way would be to draw the tree of decision points:"
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:69
msgid ""
"If you combine the two together, you'll notice that they don't map onto one "
"another perfectly. The decision tree slices the view we created in "
"`InnerComponent` into three pieces, and combines part of `InnerComponent` "
"with the `OddDuck` component:"
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:80
msgid "Looking at this table, I notice the following things:"
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:81
msgid ""
"The component tree and the decision tree don't match one another: the \"is "
"count even?\" decision splits `<InnerComponent/>` into three parts (one that "
"never changes, one if even, one if odd), and merges one of these with the "
"`<OddDuck/>` component."
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:82
msgid ""
"The decision tree and the list of side effects correspond perfectly: each "
"side effect is created at a specific decision point."
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:83
msgid ""
"The decision tree and the tree of data also line up. It's hard to see with "
"only one signal in the table, but unlike a component, which is a function "
"that can include multiple decisions or none, a signal is always created at a "
"specific line in the tree of decisions."
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:85
msgid ""
"Here's the thing: The structure of your data and the structure of side "
"effects affect the actual functionality of your application. The structure "
"of your components is just a convenience of authoring. You don't care, and "
"you shouldn't care, which component rendered which `<p>` tag, or which "
"component created the effect to log the values. All that matters is that "
"they happen at the right times."
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:87
msgid ""
"In Leptos, _components do not exist._ That is to say: You can write your "
"application as a tree of components, because that's convenient, and we "
"provide some debugging tools and logging built around components, because "
"that's convenient too. But your components do not exist at runtime: "
"Components are not a unit of change detection or of rendering. They are "
"simply function calls. You can write your whole application in one big "
"component, or split it into a hundred components, and it does not affect the "
"runtime behavior, because components don't really exist."
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:89
msgid ""
"The decision tree, on the other hand, _does exist_. And it's really "
"important!"
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:91
msgid "The Decision Tree, Rendering, and Ownership"
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:93
msgid ""
"Every decision point is some kind of reactive statement: a signal or a "
"function that can change over time. When you pass a signal or a function "
"into the renderer, it automatically wraps it in an effect that subscribes to "
"any signals it contains, and updates the view accordingly over time."
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:95
msgid ""
"This means that when your application is rendered, it creates a tree of "
"nested effects that perfectly mirrors the decision tree. In pseudo-code:"
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:97
msgid "// root\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:98
msgid "/* render the <button> once */"
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:99
msgid "// the renderer wraps an effect around the `move || if count() ...`\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:103
msgid "/* render the even <p> */"
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:105
msgid "// the user created an effect to log the count\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:110
msgid "/* render the <p> from OddDuck */"
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:111
msgid "/* render the second <p> */"
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:113
msgid "// the renderer creates an effect to update the second <p>\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:115
msgid "// update the content of the <p> with the signal\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:122
msgid ""
"Each reactive value is wrapped in its own effect to update the DOM, or run "
"any other side effects of changes to signals. But you don't need these "
"effects to keep running forever. For example, when `count` switches from an "
"odd number back to an even number, the second `<p>` no longer exists, so the "
"effect to keep updating it is no longer useful. Instead of running forever, "
"effects are canceled when the decision that created them changes. In other "
"words, and more precisely: effects are canceled whenever the effect that was "
"running when they were created re-runs. If they were created in a "
"conditional branch, and re-running the effect goes through the same branch, "
"the effect will be created again: if not, it will not."
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:124
msgid ""
"From the perspective of the reactive system itself, your application's "
"\"decision tree\" is really a reactive \"ownership tree.\" Simply put, a "
"reactive \"owner\" is the effect or memo that is currently running. It owns "
"effects created within it, they own their own children, and so on. When an "
"effect is going to re-run, it first \"cleans up\" its children, then runs "
"again."
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:126
msgid ""
"So far, this model is shared with the reactive system as it exists in "
"JavaScript frameworks like S.js or Solid, in which the concept of ownership "
"exists to automatically cancel effects."
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:128
msgid ""
"What Leptos adds is that we add a second, similar meaning to ownership: a "
"reactive owner not only owns its child effects, so that it can cancel them; "
"it also owns its signals (memos, etc.) so that it can dispose of them."
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:130
msgid "Ownership and the `Copy` Arena"
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:132
msgid ""
"This is the innovation that allows Leptos to be usable as a Rust UI "
"framework. Traditionally, managing UI state in Rust has been hard, because "
"UI is all about shared mutability. (A simple counter button is enough to see "
"the problem: You need both immutable access to set the text node showing the "
"counter's value, and mutable access in the click handler, and every Rust UI "
"framework is designed around the fact that Rust is designed to prevent "
"exactly that!) Using something like an event handler in Rust traditionally "
"relies on primitives for communicating via shared memory with interior "
"mutability (`Rc<RefCell<_>>`, `Arc<Mutex<_>>`) or for shared memory by "
"communicating via channels, either of which often requires explicit `."
"clone()`ing to be moved into an event listener. This is kind of fine, but "
"also an enormous inconvenience."
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:134
msgid ""
"Leptos has always used a form of arena allocation for signals instead. A "
"signal itself is essentially an index into a data structure that's held "
"elsewhere. It's a cheap-to-copy integer type that does not do reference "
"counting on its own, so it can be copied around, moved into event listeners, "
"etc. without explicit cloning."
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:136
msgid ""
"Instead of Rust lifetimes or reference counting, the life cycles of these "
"signals are determined by the ownership tree."
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:138
msgid ""
"Just as all effects belong to an owning parent effect, and the children are "
"canceled when the owner reruns, so too all signals belong to an owner, and "
"are disposed of when the parent reruns."
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:140
msgid ""
"In most cases, this is completely fine. Imagine that in our example above, "
"`<OddDuck/>` created some other signal that it used to update part of its "
"UI. In most cases, that signal will be used for local state in that "
"component, or maybe passed down as a prop to another component. It's unusual "
"for it to be hoisted up out of the decision tree and used somewhere else in "
"the application. When the `count` switches back to an even number, it is no "
"longer needed and can be disposed."
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:142
msgid "However, this means there are two possible issues that can arise."
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:144
msgid "Signals can be used after they are disposed"
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:146
msgid ""
"The `ReadSignal` or `WriteSignal` that you hold is just an integer: say, 3 "
"if it's the 3rd signal in the application. (As always, the reality is a bit "
"more complicated, but not much.) You can copy that number all over the place "
"and use it to say, \"Hey, get me signal 3.\" When the owner cleans up, the "
"_value_ of signal 3 will be invalidated; but the number 3 that you've copied "
"all over the place can't be invalidated. (Not without a whole garbage "
"collector!) That means that if you push signals back \"up\" the decision "
"tree, and store them somewhere conceptually \"higher\" in your application "
"than they were created, they can be accessed after being disposed."
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:148
msgid ""
"If you try to _update_ a signal after it was disposed, nothing bad really "
"happens. The framework will just warn you that you tried to update a signal "
"that no longer exists. But if you try to _access_ one, there's no coherent "
"answer other than panicking: there is no value that could be returned. "
"(There are `try_` equivalents to the `.get()` and `.with()` methods that "
"will simply return `None` if a signal has been disposed)."
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:150
msgid ""
"Signals can be leaked if you create them in a higher scope and never dispose "
"of them"
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:152
msgid ""
"The opposite is also true, and comes up particularly when working with "
"collections of signals, like an `RwSignal<Vec<RwSignal<_>>>`. If you create "
"a signal at a higher level, and pass it down to a component at a lower "
"level, it is not disposed until the higher-up owner is cleaned up."
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:154
msgid ""
"For example, if you have a todo app that creates a new `RwSignal<Todo>` for "
"each todo, stores it in an `RwSignal<Vec<RwSignal<Todo>>>`, and then passes "
"it down to a `<Todo/>`, that signal is not automatically disposed when you "
"remove the todo from the list, but must be manually disposed, or it will "
"\"leak\" for as long as its owner is still alive. (See the [TodoMVC example]"
"(https://github.com/leptos-rs/leptos/blob/main/examples/todomvc/src/lib."
"rs#L77-L85) for more discussion.)"
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:156
msgid ""
"This is only an issue when you create signals, store them in a collection, "
"and remove them from the collection without manually disposing of them as "
"well."
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:158
msgid "Solving these Problems with Reference-Counted Signals"
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:160
msgid ""
"0.7 introduces a reference-counted equivalent for each of our arena-"
"allocated primitive: for every `RwSignal` there is an `ArcRwSignal` "
"(`ArcReadSignal`, `ArcWriteSignal`, `ArcMemo`, and so on)."
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:162
msgid ""
"These have their memory and disposal managed by reference counting, rather "
"than the ownership tree."
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:164
msgid ""
"This means that they can safely be used in situations in which the arena-"
"allocated equivalents would either be leaked or used after being disposed."
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:166
msgid ""
"This is especially useful when creating collections of signals: you might "
"create `ArcRwSignal<_>` instead of `RwSignal<_>`, and then convert it into "
"an `RwSignal<_>` in each row of a table, for example."
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:168
msgid ""
"See the use of `ArcRwSignal<i32>` in the [`counters` example](https://github."
"com/leptos-rs/leptos/blob/main/examples/counters/src/lib.rs) for a more "
"concrete example."
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:170
msgid "Connecting the Dots"
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:172
msgid ""
"The answers to the questions we started with should probably make some sense "
"now."
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:174
msgid "Component Life-Cycle"
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:176
msgid ""
"There is no component life-cycle, because components don't really exist. But "
"there is an ownership lifecycle, and you can use it to accomplish the same "
"things:"
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:177
msgid ""
"_before mount_: simply running code in the body of a component will run it "
"\"before the component mounts\""
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:178
msgid ""
"_on mount_: `create_effect` runs a tick after the rest of the component, so "
"it can be useful for effects that need to wait for the view to be mounted to "
"the DOM."
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:179
msgid ""
"_on unmount_: You can use `on_cleanup` to give the reactive system code that "
"should run while the current owner is cleaning up, before running again. "
"Because an owner is around a \"decision,\" this means that `on_cleanup` will "
"run when your component unmounts: if something can unmount, the renderer "
"must have created an effect that's unmounting it!"
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:181
msgid "Issues with Disposed Signals"
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:183
msgid ""
"Generally speaking, problems can only arise here if you are creating a "
"signal lower down in the ownership tree and storing it somewhere higher up. "
"If you run into issues here, you should instead \"hoist\" the signal "
"creation up into the parent, and then pass the created signals downâ€”making "
"sure to dispose of them on removal, if needed!"
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:185
msgid "`Copy` signals"
msgstr ""

#: src/appendix_life_cycle.md:187
msgid ""
"The whole system of `Copy`able wrapper types (signals, `StoredValue`, and so "
"on) uses the ownership tree as a close approximation of the life-cycle of "
"different parts of your UI. In effect, it parallels the Rust language's "
"system of lifetimes based on blocks of code with a system of lifetimes based "
"on sections of UI. This can't always be perfectly checked at compile time, "
"but overall we think it's a net positive."
msgstr ""
